headline: Norway wealth fund to vote against Musk's $1 trillion Tesla package
summary: STORY: Norway's sovereign wealth fund is the world's largest.And on Tuesday it said it would vote against approving Tesla CEO Elon Musk's proposed compensation package, containing shares worth up to $1 trillion.Investors in the electric-vehicle maker will decide on November 6 whether to confirm the package.It's thought to be the largest-ever CEO compensation agreement and critics have called it excessive.So far, the Norwegian wealth fund is the largest outside Tesla investor to say how it plans to vote.The next-largest to do so, Baron Capital, on Monday said it would support Musk's pay package.Other major investors like BlackRock, Vanguard and State Street have yet to disclose their voting plans.Tesla's board is pushing for shareholders to approve the plan.Its chair warned last week Musk could leave the company if the deal is rejected.While the package could grant stock worth up to $1 trillion over 10 years, the cost of those shares at the time of the award will be deducted.According to Reuters analysis, that will make the value to Musk slightly lower, at up to $878 billion,.The $2.1 trillion Norwegian fund also said it would vote against Tesla's proposed general stock compensation plan.It's intended for all employees and can also be used by the board to benefit Musk.

headline: Wall Street Intensifies Scrutiny of Fraud After Spate of Loan Losses
summary: A string of alleged frauds by corporate borrowers is spurring a reckoning across Wall Street, sending bankers and investors scrambling to prevent future blowups.  Lenders are increasing due diligence and demanding a longer history of financial data from companies.  A group of the biggest names in banking, investment management and accounting have formed a task force that will take a deeper look at the nature of the problem and how to protect investors.
